The RIPS project focused on comparing the centralized versus decentralized infrastructure for water, energy, and transportation, with specific attention to potential costs or benefits from linkages between these infrastructure systems. The central hypothesis of the project is that interconnected and decentralized infrastructure systems are more resilient than isolated and centralized infrastructure by increasing response diversity. A secondary hypothesis is that decentralized infrastructure systems are more scalable and adaptable to change. In other words, it is simpler to add smaller increments of infrastructure on an as needed basis. The Georgia Tech RIPS project tested these hypotheses by studying the resilience of centralized versus decentralized water, energy, and transportation (WET) systems at the metropolitan, city, community, and household level using Atlanta, GA as a test bed.

The primary finding of this multi-year study is that decentralized water, energy, and transportation infrastructure may have a higher impact on reducing greenhouse gas emissions and water-for-energy consumption than land-use changes. Costs and benefits, however, are dependent on the degree and the method in which multiple infrastructure systems can be integrated at the household, neighborhood, and metropolitan area scales. To draw these conclusions researchers studied:

Water pricing, subsidies for adopting water conserving approaches, and their effects on water demand;
Feed in tariff rates and other policies that affect the adoption of solar photovoltaic systems;
The use of rainwater harvesting, stormwater reuse, and rooftop solar PV;
Differences in water use among single-family and multi-family households, and further distinguished by home size, building age, and socio-economic characteristics of the occupants;
The use of novel water treatment methods by industry to recycle water locally;
Differences between using natural gas and landfill gas to generate electricity;
Effects of neighborhood design, size, density, and connectivity on transportation demand and the potential for rooftop solar PV;
Energy that is embodied within the building inventory and how this has historically changed over time;
The costs and potential of Combined Cooling Heating and Power systems to mitigate the emissions of carbon and other pollutants and to use water, at both the household level and across the metropolitan Atlanta region;
Impacts of Transit Oriented Development on travel demand, walkability, housing affordability, and neighborhood desirability;
The potential of Shared Autonomous Vehicles to alter travel demand, to change settlement patterns, to influence labor accessibility and industrial agglomeration, and to shape urban redevelopment as demand for parking changes; and
The use of Low Impact Development principles to manage storm water locally and across the region.


In conducting these studies, researchers also developed several models and new computational methods for linking together and simultaneously running multiple large water, energy, and transportation models. This included an integrated simulation model that incorporated urban growth scenarios, water demand projections, and multiple different decentralized urban water systems to study the long-term benefits and costs of decentralized water infrastructures. In another model, natural, physical and cyber- attacks on the electric grid were simulated, and counterattack strategies were tested in order to help understand the threats to and the resilience of different central and decentralized electric power systems. In still another project, new parallel simulation algorithms were developed that improve the efficiency of running multiple models simultaneously and enable the rapid integration with other simulation tools.

Finally, the team used a unique database of 2,000 North American aging shopping centers, office parks and other parking-dominated properties to explore the gap between idealized models of infrastructure integration and their real-world implementation. Approximately half of the retrofits aimed to improve walkability, bikability and transit, as well as some green infrastructure to handle stormwater on site. There were also significant increases in social infrastructure. Overall, a wide range of positive performance was found, confirming that sustainable and resilient infrastructure improvements are being implemented in suburban retrofits, but the opportunity to fully take advantage of many of the technologies and approaches studied here remains largely unrealized.

With funding from the National Science Foundation, this study produced 58 publications and supported the work of 13 Investigators, 3 Postdoctoral Scholars, and 30 Graduate Research Assistants. The findings from this project were published in peer-reviewed journals, including PNAS, Journal of Cleaner Production, Environmental Science and Technology, Journal of the American Planning Association, the Journal of Urban Affairs, and Urban Studies. The findings were also disseminated in academic conferences, including the Association of Environmental Engineering and Science Professors Annual Conference, and the National Academy of Science Annual Conference; and to local government officials and commercial developers including the Atlanta Regional Commission and Disney Shanghai Research Lab.

